U.S-led forces started air strikes against Islamic State
group in Syria and Iraq in the summer. Washington has said the
campaign in Syria is not coordinated with the Syrian military,
which also views the group as its enemy.

The war has killed more than 200,000 people and displaced
close to half the population, according to the United Nations.
Damascus accuses its Western and Gulf Arab opponents of seeking
to destroy the country by providing aid to an insurgency now
dominated by jihadists, who also pose a threat to the West.

Assad appears to be betting that the U.S.-led campaign
against Islamic State will force Washington to engage with him.

